# Enterprise OS Hardening and Incident Response Framework

## Research-Oriented Cybersecurity Case Study

This repository presents a cybersecurity case study focused on enterprise operating system hardening, network traffic analysis, malware delivery investigation, and brute-force attack mitigation within a simulated enterprise web infrastructure.

The project demonstrates how modern cyber attacks exploit weak authentication controls, insecure web application behaviour, and insufficient system hardening to compromise enterprise environments. The investigation combines network forensics, OS hardening, threat detection engineering, and enterprise remediation planning aligned with contemporary cybersecurity operations.

---

# Executive Problem Statement

Modern enterprise infrastructures remain vulnerable to application-layer attacks, credential abuse, and malicious payload delivery through trusted web services. Attackers increasingly leverage weak password policies, insecure administrative access, and social engineering techniques to compromise organizational assets and distribute malware to end users.

This project investigates a simulated enterprise web compromise in which attackers manipulated a legitimate website to distribute a malicious payload over the HTTP protocol after gaining unauthorized administrative access through a suspected brute-force attack.

The objective of this repository is to analyze the incident from both a network forensic and enterprise hardening perspective while proposing resilient operating system security controls and detection strategies suitable for modern cybersecurity operations centers (SOC environments).

